{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Descartes explicitly states that virtue is sufficient for attaining happiness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "In this paper I argue that, within the framework he develops, this is not exactly true: more than virtuous action is needed to secure happiness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "To be happy, we need to connect virtuous action to a specific intellectual insight into ourselves and the world at large.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "For Descartes, moral agency is about the correct use of our will, which consists of both a cognitive and a conative component.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "The highest good equals virtuous action, which involves two components, judging well and striving to act according to one's judgment.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Happiness, in turn, is not the highest good but something that is supposed to follow from it.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Securing happiness requires that we have a rather multifaceted intellectual insight into virtuous action.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The third condition according to which we must understand that if we use our will correctly, all the good things we do not attain are outside our power.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Nothing can impede our contentment except desire and regret or repentance.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Fulfilling the third condition protects us from them so that we will be happy should we also have fulfilled the first two conditions by acting virtuously.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "We have no reason to repent anything we do provided that we have judged the situation to the best of our abilities and genuinely tried to act accordingly.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Realizing this guards us against the three potential threats to happiness provided that we have done everything within our power by acting virtuously.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "It is a plain mistake to want anything not dependent on us to have been otherwise.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Realizing this, Descartes argues, is enough to subdue our desires and regrets concerning things outside our control that could threaten our peace of mind or happiness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "The Cartesian account of the path from virtue to happiness involves an intellectual insight consisting of three key components: (1) the distinction between what is and what is not up to us, (2) the idea that we are not to blame ourselves for anything we do as long as we have genuinely done our best to judge correctly and act accordingly, and (3) the view that things outside our power are determined by providence.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Descartes downplays the intellectual insight his account involves because he thinks that all of its three main components are innocuous in their ubiquity.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "The highest good equals virtuous action, which involves two components, judging well and striving to act according to one's judgment.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Happiness, in turn, is not the highest good but something that is supposed to follow from it.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
