      "text": "virtue is almost - but not quite - enough for attaining happiness. To be happy, we need to connect virtuous action to a specific intellectual insight into ourselves and the world at large.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "4": {
      "text": "For Descartes, virtue is primarily about exerting ourselves according to our best judgment.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "5": {
      "text": "acting virtuously equals acting in accordance with the two-component theory.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "6": {
      "text": "for Descartes happiness is about having a contented mind, but it is not our highest good: being virtuous - using one's will as the two-component theory states - is.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "7": {
      "text": "the Cartesian account of the path from virtue to happiness involves - in addition to acting virtuously - an intellectual insight consisting of three key components: (1) the distinction between what is and what is not up to us, (2) the idea that we are not to blame ourselves for anything we do as long as we have genuinely done our best to judge correctly and act accordingly, and (3) the view that things outside our power are determined by providence.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
